skos:closeMatch is used to link two concepts that are sufficiently similar that they can be used interchangeably in some information retrieval applications. In order to avoid the possibility of 'compound errors' when combining mappings across more than two concept schemes, skos:closeMatch is not declared to be a transitive property

The SRD is a plane that sits above the highest elevation in the data. In a land project with a seismic reference datum set, the SRD will have a time of 0 ms. All time data, e.g. seismic and velocities, will start at this datum.

The point or level from which heights and depths are measured and referenced to for an entity or activity. Typically these are expressed relative to a common global or regional reference datum such as the Australian Height Datum (AHD) or can be related to local reference systems. Specific emphasis is placed on elevation references used by resource exploration and drilling programs, whereby depths are measured relative to local reference datums or specific parts of a borehole/drilling platform. Concepts in this vocabulary include both reference datums (e.g. mean sea level) and how depths are expressed relative to them (e.g. mean sea level height).

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: A seismic reference datum (SRD) is used in land seismic projects as a reference surface to counteract the fact that elevation on land is variable. An SRD is a plane that sits above the highest elevation in the data. In a land project with a seismic reference datum set, the SRD will have a time of 0 ms. All time data, for example seismic and velocities, will start at this datum. Marine seismic is usually referenced to mean sea level (MSL), a global datum for measuring height. In a marine project, zero elevation (the mean sea level) will have a time of 0 ms.
